AWS 3-Tier Architecture Hands-On Guide
1️⃣ Create VPC
Go to VPC Dashboard → Your VPCs → Create VPC
Configure:
Name: my-vpc
IPv4 CIDR block: 10.0.0.0/16
Tenancy: Default
Click Create VPC
2️⃣ Create Subnets

Public Subnet

Name: public-subnet
IPv4 CIDR: 10.0.1.0/24
Auto-assign public IPv4: Enable

Private Subnet

Name: private-subnet
IPv4 CIDR: 10.0.2.0/24
Auto-assign public IPv4: Disable
3️⃣ Create Internet Gateway (IGW)
Go to Internet Gateways → Create Internet Gateway
Name: my-igw
Attach to my-vpc
4️⃣ Create Route Tables

Public Route Table

Associate with Public Subnet
Add route: 0.0.0.0/0 → my-igw

Private Route Table

Associate with Private Subnet
Initially empty; will add NAT route next
5️⃣ Create NAT Gateway
Go to NAT Gateways → Create NAT Gateway
Subnet: Public Subnet
Allocate New Elastic IP
Click Create NAT Gateway
Update Private Route Table:
Route 0.0.0.0/0 → NAT Gateway
6️⃣ Create Security Groups

Public SG (Web/ALB)

SSH (22) from your IP
HTTP (80), HTTPS (443) from anywhere

Private SG (DB/App)

Allow traffic only from Public SG
Optional: SSH from Public SG

ALB SG

HTTP/HTTPS from anywhere
7️⃣ Launch EC2 Instances

Public EC2 (Web Tier)

Subnet: Public Subnet
Attach: Public SG
User Data to install Apache:
#!/bin/bash
sudo yum update -y
sudo yum install -y httpd
sudo systemctl start httpd
sudo systemctl enable httpd
Verify SSH access from your IP

Private EC2 (App/DB Tier)

Subnet: Private Subnet
Attach: Private SG
No public IP
Connect via jump host (public EC2 SSH)
8️⃣ Install Database on Private Server (Optional)
SSH into Public EC2
From there, SSH into Private EC2
Install MySQL/PostgreSQL or other DB
9️⃣ Create Launch Template & Auto Scaling Group (ASG)

Launch Template

AMI: Amazon Linux 2 / Ubuntu
Instance type: e.g., t3.micro
Security Group: Public SG
User Data: install Apache

Auto Scaling Group (ASG)

Subnet: Public Subnet
Min/Max/Desired instances: e.g., 1/4/2
Attach Target Group for ALB
🔟 Create Application Load Balancer (ALB)
ALB → Subnet: Public Subnet(s)
Attach ALB SG
Create Target Group
Port: 80
Protocol: HTTP
Health Check: /
Create Listener: HTTP 80 → forward to Target Group
1️⃣1️⃣ Optional: Route 53 Integration
Create Hosted Zone, e.g., myapp.com
Create A Record → Alias → ALB
Users can now access the app via domain
✅ Benefits
High Availability → Multiple web servers behind ALB
Scalability → ASG adds/removes instances automatically
Security → Private subnet isolated; SGs control traffic
Internet Access → Public server directly, private via NAT
DNS & Reliability → ALB + Route 53 provides stable access